= Strasser's Resignation

Arguably the second most powerful man in the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>, just behind [+ nsdap_leader +] himself, Gregor Strasser, has resigned from his party posts! As head of the party organization and standard-bearer of its "left wing", Strasser had built a reputation as a sober and pragmatic counterbalance in a movement otherwise dominated by fanatics. 

A realist, Strasser believed the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span> could not win a majority at the ballot box and should have participated in the Papen cabinet when their bargaining power was strongest. His deep understanding of the grassroots conditions had led him to predict that another election would devastate the party’s support and morale, ultimately drying up their funding.

Disillusionment with [+ nsdap_leader +]’s rigid, all-or-nothing strategy had been building for months. Strasser was reportedly authorized to negotiate the final terms of a deal for <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazi</span> participation in a Schleicher-led cabinet. Yet, at the last moment, [+ nsdap_leader +] reversed himself—abruptly rejecting the plan under influence from Goebbels and Göring during a party leadership meeting.

For Strasser, this last-minute betrayal was the breaking point. He openly criticized [+ nsdap_leader +]’s indecisiveness, declaring that he would even support a violent seizure of power—if a clear order were given. The final straw came when [+ nsdap_leader +] publicly addressed the party’s parliamentary delegation, proclaiming: “A great movement has never triumphed by taking the path of compromise”.

