However, nothing ever happens. After sending a letter to [+ nsdap_leader +] explaining his reasons for resigning, Strasser quietly departs on a two-week vacation to northern Italy. In a letter, he assures [+ nsdap_leader +] that he has no intention of becoming "the focal point of oppositional efforts or even of discussions thereof." Strasser is not a fighter like his brother; he has squandered his chance to trigger a meaningful defection—potentially involving sixty Reichstag deputies.

This was not part of any grand plan by Schleicher to split the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>. In fact, the loss of his closest potential "ally" within the party has effectively ended Schleicher’s hopes of using his influence to convince the broader party to tolerate his government.

For the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">**NSDAP**</span>, losing their most effective organizational leader is a serious blow. Across Germany, a growing sense emerges: the <span style="color: #7A3C00;">Nazis</span> have peaked, and their internal contradictions will soon begin pitting the movement against itself. However, Hitler’s threat of suicide, his impassioned pleas, and his charismatic presence have so far held the party together—preventing others from following Strasser’s lead, at least for now. Publicly, Hitler claims that Strasser has merely requested sick leave, softening the immediate impact.

> *"If the party falls apart... I’ll finish myself off with a pistol within three minutes."*

 - Adolf Hitler to Joseph Goebbels, [+ year +]

